To make the photo scrolling in the background less distracting and have less opacity, you can adjust the opacity of the `.background` class in your CSS code. To have it scroll in the background as the user scrolls down the website, you can set the `background-attachment` property to `scroll`. Here's an updated CSS code snippet:

```
.background {
  height: 100vh;
  background-image: url("../images/photo1.jpg");
  background-size: cover;
  background-repeat: no-repeat;
  background-attachment: scroll;
  animation: scroll 60s linear infinite;
  opacity: 0.5; /* set the opacity to 50% */
}

@keyframes scroll {
  0% {
    background-position: 0% 0%;
  }
  100% {
    background-position: 0% 100%;
  }
}
```

With these changes, the background image will be less distracting and scroll in the background as the user scrolls down the website.

